1
00:02:21,453 --> 00:02:26,032
When he didn't come to the office,
10:30, 11:00...

2
00:02:27,584 --> 00:02:29,624
...I called the house.

3
00:02:29,795 --> 00:02:31,123
Catharine...

4
00:02:31,672 --> 00:02:34,957
...he went in his sleep,
so peacefully.

5
00:02:36,134 --> 00:02:38,460
The doctor said if you slept
next to him...

6
00:02:38,637 --> 00:02:41,258
...you wouldn't even have known.

7
00:02:41,598 --> 00:02:44,552
You couldn't have done anything.

8
00:02:55,821 --> 00:02:57,897
Mrs. Petersen.

9
00:02:58,156 --> 00:03:01,442
- Catharine, let me come up with you.
- No.

10
00:03:01,618 --> 00:03:04,191
You get some rest, Sara.

11
00:05:19,630 --> 00:05:22,299
Nice blouse, Alex.
- Has been for years, Michael.

12
00:05:22,466 --> 00:05:25,633
I'm late. I spent the whole morning
going over obituaries.

13
00:05:25,803 --> 00:05:27,345
The whole morning?

14
00:05:27,513 --> 00:05:30,383
<i>Yeah. Detroit Free Press on your list?
April 12th.</i>

15
00:05:30,557 --> 00:05:33,760
I don't roll out of bed
and read obituaries before coffee.

16
00:05:33,936 --> 00:05:37,305
Wasn't this guy a capo for Marangano
a few years back?

17
00:05:37,481 --> 00:05:38,809
- So?
- So...

18
00:05:38,982 --> 00:05:42,766
...two guys die within four days
of each other. What does that say?

19
00:05:42,945 --> 00:05:46,989
No pattern. This guy could've been
a hit, but Marangano died in his sleep.

20
00:05:47,157 --> 00:05:49,482
He stopped breathing.
They ran a full...

21
00:05:49,660 --> 00:05:51,486
- Not now.
Is that what Bruce thinks?

22
00:05:51,662 --> 00:05:52,693
Alex.

23
00:05:52,871 --> 00:05:57,035
A government pouch to someone's
home is illegal. Worse, it's expensive.

24
00:05:57,209 --> 00:06:00,827
Well, my contribution
to the federal deficit.

25
00:06:03,799 --> 00:06:08,544
And let go of this Marangano thing.
People die in their sleep. Even dons.

26
00:06:08,720 --> 00:06:10,677
It was a hit!
Hey, keep it down.

27
00:06:10,847 --> 00:06:13,172
He ran trash collection
for half of Jersey.

28
00:06:13,350 --> 00:06:16,019
- You don't die in your sleep of...
Ondine's Curse.

29
00:06:16,186 --> 00:06:19,851
"Damage of unknown origin to the part
of the brain that controls breathing."

30
00:06:20,023 --> 00:06:21,850
It's rare. It's real. It happens.

31
00:06:22,275 --> 00:06:26,854
Yeah, I'm here six years, it never
happened. You do a run on it?

32
00:06:30,700 --> 00:06:33,072
- This the only one?
- It can't be connected.

33
00:06:33,244 --> 00:06:37,408
This guy's not Mafia. He's some
millionaire publisher from New York.

34
00:06:37,582 --> 00:06:38,910
"Cause of death unknown.

35
00:06:39,083 --> 00:06:42,120
Evidence suggests unexplained
interruption of breathing.

36
00:06:42,295 --> 00:06:44,584
Consider possibility of Ondine's Curse.

37
00:06:44,756 --> 00:06:49,501
Sam Petersen, age 60. Survived
by his wife of four months, Catharine...

38
00:06:49,677 --> 00:06:54,007
...age 31."
- And I had to go back a year to get that.

39
00:06:55,433 --> 00:07:00,676
Alex, it's the only one. Believe me.
Believe me, there's nothing there.

40
00:07:16,412 --> 00:07:19,863
I've got it sitting right here
in front of me.

41
00:07:20,041 --> 00:07:24,703
Walter, you see, I don't know how
to read the goddamn instructions.

42
00:07:24,879 --> 00:07:28,129
I'm only 5 fucking years old.

43
00:07:28,299 --> 00:07:32,795
Now, you be my daddy,
and you tell me how to use it.

44
00:07:32,970 --> 00:07:35,592
Nice and simple.

45
00:07:36,182 --> 00:07:41,603
Oh, you're goddamn right I'm serious.
But my bride is here for our luncheon.

46
00:07:41,771 --> 00:07:44,688
Well, I've never been
anybody's daddy neither.

47
00:07:44,857 --> 00:07:49,685
But if you want me to pop for 200,000
units of this little plastic turd here...

48
00:07:49,862 --> 00:07:52,270
...I suggest that you start faking it.

49
00:07:52,948 --> 00:07:57,028
<i>How's that wife of yours?
- She don't look so good today.</i>

50
00:07:57,203 --> 00:08:00,702
<i>- She's the best-looking gal in Dallas.
- She looks kind of scrag.</i>

51
00:08:00,873 --> 00:08:03,280
<i>Scraggly, my ass.</i>

52
00:08:03,792 --> 00:08:06,248
Write some of these instructions
in English.

53
00:08:06,420 --> 00:08:09,587
<i>- Maybe you can find a market for this.
- I'm on top of it.</i>

54
00:08:09,757 --> 00:08:12,841
Yeah, okay, yeah. So long, then.

55
00:08:14,595 --> 00:08:18,806
Marielle, you think anybody's gonna
be interested in a thing like this?

56
00:08:18,974 --> 00:08:24,265
It's about winning, Ben.
Everybody's interested in winning.

57
00:08:24,438 --> 00:08:27,107
They forgot that they're
making this toy for kids.

58
00:08:27,274 --> 00:08:30,228
The instructions are too complicated.

59
00:08:34,198 --> 00:08:35,858
Hot damn!

60
00:09:56,613 --> 00:09:59,530
I gotta be the world's
number one airhead.

61
00:09:59,699 --> 00:10:03,910
Be gone five days, and I'm packing
half of Neiman Marcus here.

62
00:10:06,414 --> 00:10:07,742
Marielle?

63
00:10:07,915 --> 00:10:09,742
Yeah, hon?

64
00:10:10,793 --> 00:10:13,331
How come we run out of brandy
so quick, hon?

65
00:10:13,796 --> 00:10:17,046
Didn't I see a fresh bottle
in the cabinet?

66
00:10:27,143 --> 00:10:29,432
Right again, hon.

67
00:10:49,081 --> 00:10:54,870
Marielle, I've explained to Etta
that this will is valid in all respects.

68
00:10:55,045 --> 00:10:59,423
Any contest here would just be
a waste of time and money.

69
00:10:59,800 --> 00:11:01,508
My time.

70
00:11:01,677 --> 00:11:03,171
My money.

71
00:11:04,054 --> 00:11:09,345
What, a man cuts his only sister out of
his will two months after marrying a...?

72
00:11:09,518 --> 00:11:11,096
Younger woman?

73
00:11:13,314 --> 00:11:16,480
You know something, Etta,
your husband is right.

74
00:11:16,650 --> 00:11:19,022
Ben had no quarrel with you.

75
00:11:19,194 --> 00:11:22,444
Only the way you felt about me.

76
00:11:23,532 --> 00:11:26,403
I think, if he were here...

77
00:11:27,077 --> 00:11:30,161
...he'd regret what he'd done.

78
00:11:34,042 --> 00:11:35,869
Martin?

79
00:11:36,044 --> 00:11:38,915
What are the tax consequences
if I make a small gift?

80
00:11:39,089 --> 00:11:41,331
Young lady...

81
00:11:42,342 --> 00:11:46,174
Marielle is going to go back
to Charleston...

82
00:11:46,346 --> 00:11:51,803
...and she doesn't want any
harsh feelings or needless delays.

83
00:11:52,936 --> 00:11:56,186
How small a gift, dear?

84
00:12:02,154 --> 00:12:05,605
Something in the mid-six figures?

85
00:12:17,252 --> 00:12:20,621
Miss Barnes! Miss Barnes?

86
00:12:20,797 --> 00:12:23,798
Miss Barnes, can I look
in your purse, please?

87
00:12:27,095 --> 00:12:28,969
Here she comes!

88
00:12:38,481 --> 00:12:40,937
What? You gonna knock over
a liquor store?

89
00:12:41,109 --> 00:12:45,687
I was just at the target range.
I'm trying to get certified, that's all.

90
00:12:46,489 --> 00:12:50,403
I tell you what.
Send the piece back to Sears.

91
00:12:55,665 --> 00:12:57,622
Remember that Ondine's Curse thing?

92
00:13:01,713 --> 00:13:04,382
Another one came up today.

93
00:13:04,799 --> 00:13:08,049
This guy died 10 days ago.

94
00:13:21,566 --> 00:13:22,976
Dinner?

95
00:13:23,151 --> 00:13:24,561
What?

96
00:13:24,735 --> 00:13:29,314
- I said, dinner? Eat? Tonight?
- I have work left.

97
00:13:29,490 --> 00:13:32,574
Fine. Tomorrow?

98
00:13:32,743 --> 00:13:35,910
I don't think it's a good idea.
We work together.

99
00:13:36,080 --> 00:13:39,164
What, office policy? What?

100
00:13:39,542 --> 00:13:41,997
Okay. I resign.

101
00:13:43,754 --> 00:13:46,921
I can't afford to lose you.
You're my right arm.

102
00:13:48,759 --> 00:13:50,088
Okay.

103
00:13:56,100 --> 00:13:58,721
What did you say about Ondine's Curse?

104
00:13:58,894 --> 00:14:01,219
- It's not Mafia.
- What is it?

105
00:14:01,397 --> 00:14:04,813
It's a toy manufacturer from Dallas.

106
00:14:04,984 --> 00:14:10,274
He's very rich. He's very clean.
I'll get you a printout tomorrow, okay?

107
00:14:13,659 --> 00:14:15,984
- Good night.
- Good night.

108
00:14:20,290 --> 00:14:22,248
Michael.

109
00:14:22,710 --> 00:14:24,583
Wait up.

110
00:14:24,753 --> 00:14:27,161
I'm gonna go with you.

111
00:14:30,926 --> 00:14:33,417
Could a Texas toy mogul
have a mob connection?

112
00:14:33,595 --> 00:14:36,513
The Texan's a ringer
for that other guy from New York.

113
00:14:36,682 --> 00:14:39,469
How's that?
- Well, both older guys, very rich...

114
00:14:39,643 --> 00:14:42,679
...each married to a young gal
for a couple of months.

115
00:14:42,854 --> 00:14:46,899
- Must be kind of bad for your health.
- Hey, you got a minute?

116
00:14:56,243 --> 00:15:00,240
Make some calls to New York, Dallas.
Newspapers, whatever.

117
00:15:00,414 --> 00:15:02,572
Let's round up some photos.

118
00:15:02,749 --> 00:15:06,367
Shouldn't be hard.
They were prominent guys.

119
00:15:06,962 --> 00:15:08,954
Not the men.

120
00:15:09,131 --> 00:15:11,253
The wives.

121
00:15:31,945 --> 00:15:33,273
Okay.

122
00:15:34,781 --> 00:15:38,613
Seattle guidebooks,
Japanese cooking, what next?

123
00:15:39,202 --> 00:15:42,119
- Rare coins.
- What sort of rare coins?

124
00:15:42,288 --> 00:15:48,077
Something general for the beginner, then
something more particular. Perhaps...

125
00:15:48,253 --> 00:15:49,961
...Italy, the 19th century.

126
00:15:50,129 --> 00:15:53,166
Before the city-states were unified
or after?

127
00:15:53,341 --> 00:15:56,046
I don't know.
Which would be more...

128
00:15:57,178 --> 00:15:59,634
...unusual?

129
00:16:02,183 --> 00:16:04,508
Northwest Indians. Which tribes?

130
00:16:04,686 --> 00:16:08,055
Coast Salish, for certain.
Whatever else you have.

131
00:16:08,231 --> 00:16:11,018
Tlingit, Bella Coola, Kwakiutl.

132
00:16:11,192 --> 00:16:13,398
My primary interest is in totem poles.

133
00:16:13,569 --> 00:16:16,191
What are you,
cramming for a game show?

134
00:18:21,154 --> 00:18:24,404
No, I'll take it. Thank you.

135
00:18:49,015 --> 00:18:52,799
Come here. Come here, children.
Teachers, let's move them along.

136
00:18:53,186 --> 00:18:54,810
Come this way.

137
00:19:03,446 --> 00:19:06,151
One million dollars.

138
00:19:07,617 --> 00:19:10,190
A very generous offer, Miss Dodd...

139
00:19:10,453 --> 00:19:13,454
...but this museum does not sell
places on its board.

140
00:19:13,623 --> 00:19:14,951
- Our chairman...
- Yes.

141
00:19:15,124 --> 00:19:18,956
I'm sure Mr. McCorey will appreciate
my intentions. Good day.

142
00:19:22,465 --> 00:19:25,466
But Margaret,
we want your views on this.

143
00:19:25,635 --> 00:19:29,715
Now, I understand you had very
strong feelings about this collection.

144
00:19:29,889 --> 00:19:32,296
Mr. McCorey...

145
00:19:32,475 --> 00:19:35,511
...I didn't want my first meeting
to be one where I...

146
00:19:35,686 --> 00:19:37,180
You disagreed with anybody.

147
00:19:40,274 --> 00:19:43,275
I think it's a mistake to concentrate
so exclusively...

148
00:19:43,444 --> 00:19:45,935
...on the Coast Salish in our acquisitions.

149
00:19:46,739 --> 00:19:50,819
You want to be the best at something,
but that's not our role.

150
00:19:50,993 --> 00:19:52,487
And what is, Margaret?

151
00:19:52,661 --> 00:19:55,662
We need to compare all the tribes.

152
00:19:55,831 --> 00:19:58,916
We study their art to learn about them.

153
00:19:59,084 --> 00:20:02,916
We study them
to understand ourselves.

154
00:20:08,135 --> 00:20:11,006
These the best pictures?
She doesn't want pictures.

155
00:20:11,180 --> 00:20:13,967
She knows the camera's there.
She turns away.

156
00:20:14,141 --> 00:20:16,679
The Texas one is different,
slimmer body.

157
00:20:16,852 --> 00:20:19,177
- It's the way she's stand...
- She's younger.

158
00:20:19,355 --> 00:20:22,190
- It's makeup, hair, attitude.
- I think you're wrong.

159
00:20:22,358 --> 00:20:23,900
I could be right.

160
00:20:24,234 --> 00:20:27,603
The whole m.o., a complex series
of seductions and murders...

161
00:20:27,780 --> 00:20:30,105
...that's not something
you see a woman do.

162
00:20:30,282 --> 00:20:35,110
Oh? Which part you figure a woman isn't
up to? The seduction or the murder?

163
00:20:35,287 --> 00:20:37,908
Look, I just want the field assignment.

164
00:20:38,081 --> 00:20:40,489
- Please?
- Listen...

165
00:20:40,667 --> 00:20:43,372
...data analysis is the heart
of what we do here.

166
00:20:43,545 --> 00:20:46,914
The best work in this shop
is yours. The best.

167
00:20:47,090 --> 00:20:50,590
- It's a job you were born to do.
- It's a job with green windows!

168
00:20:50,761 --> 00:20:53,548
Bruce, I've been in this office
for six years.

169
00:20:53,722 --> 00:20:56,842
This goddamned government
office with green windows.

170
00:20:57,017 --> 00:21:01,097
You want excitement. People
don't look to get it all from their job.

171
00:21:02,314 --> 00:21:04,390
- What's that supposed to mean?
- Jesus.

172
00:21:04,566 --> 00:21:07,235
What do you think it means?
Having a date!

173
00:21:07,402 --> 00:21:11,981
When was the last time you rolled in late
on a Monday because of a big weekend?

174
00:21:12,157 --> 00:21:15,490
I really can't believe
you're saying this to me!

175
00:21:15,827 --> 00:21:18,365
I have to listen to this shit
from my mother!

176
00:21:18,538 --> 00:21:21,705
What the hell do you think
you are, Bruce?

177
00:21:26,379 --> 00:21:28,419
Look, I just...

178
00:21:31,301 --> 00:21:33,874
You're not happy.

179
00:21:34,262 --> 00:21:37,216
You're not a happy person.

180
00:21:39,267 --> 00:21:41,425
And you deserve to be, that's all.

181
00:21:42,854 --> 00:21:46,353
Bruce, make me happy.

182
00:21:56,034 --> 00:21:58,951
Even if you're right, it isn't federal.

183
00:22:01,414 --> 00:22:05,079
Whatever you can't fit on the
weekends, make sure you call in sick.

184
00:22:07,879 --> 00:22:09,207
Thanks.

185
00:22:18,598 --> 00:22:22,263
She was destroyed by his death.
They were very devoted.

186
00:22:22,435 --> 00:22:26,479
Catharine needed to get away,
and she went to Europe.

187
00:22:26,647 --> 00:22:30,016
That was over a year ago.
Have you heard from her?

188
00:22:30,192 --> 00:22:34,689
I had a postcard from Rome. I had
a lovely note from Vienna, a little gift.

189
00:22:34,864 --> 00:22:39,360
All in the first month, or thereabouts.
Anything lately?

190
00:22:39,785 --> 00:22:41,612
Only the attorney.

191
00:22:41,787 --> 00:22:45,203
He received instructions
to convert the estate into cash...

192
00:22:45,499 --> 00:22:48,286
...and to transfer the funds
to a Swiss account.

193
00:22:48,461 --> 00:22:52,293
No one else in Manhattan,
not a single soul.

194
00:22:52,465 --> 00:22:55,668
Everyone says the same thing.
From Chicago, no family...

195
00:22:55,843 --> 00:22:59,259
...they don't know where she lived,
where she worked.

196
00:23:00,472 --> 00:23:02,264
Could I have this photograph?

197
00:23:07,313 --> 00:23:11,262
I'm sorry.
That must have sounded awful.

198
00:23:13,902 --> 00:23:19,110
Sara, it's just that she came out of thin
air, and she vanished back into thin air.

199
00:23:19,283 --> 00:23:23,530
- Well, is that against the law?
- It's odd. I find it odd.

200
00:23:24,663 --> 00:23:29,870
Sam Petersen is gone.
So is all of his property, his money.

201
00:23:31,295 --> 00:23:35,079
And if I loved him as much as you did,
I'd find it very odd indeed.

202
00:23:40,304 --> 00:23:45,131
That's Felice Baciocchi
and her sister Elisa.

203
00:23:47,853 --> 00:23:51,518
You probably looked all this up
just to impress me.

204
00:23:53,317 --> 00:23:55,724
Did it work?

205
00:23:56,236 --> 00:24:02,689
Well, you know, I really did wonder.
You seem almost too good to be true.

206
00:24:03,577 --> 00:24:06,494
I thought of checking up on you.

207
00:24:11,668 --> 00:24:13,791
Not a bad thought.

208
00:24:13,962 --> 00:24:17,663
After all, I could be
practically anybody.

209
00:24:18,133 --> 00:24:21,169
Dangerous not to check people out.

210
00:24:21,344 --> 00:24:23,503
I did.

211
00:24:26,057 --> 00:24:28,762
And what did you find?

212
00:24:30,228 --> 00:24:35,567
I found that you went to Mount
Holyoke, you studied anthropology...

213
00:24:35,734 --> 00:24:39,019
...and I found...

214
00:24:39,487 --> 00:24:42,192
...we're a lot alike.

215
00:24:45,994 --> 00:24:48,995
We like Italy, and we like coins.

216
00:24:49,914 --> 00:24:51,741
And we like to live alone.

217
00:24:54,961 --> 00:24:57,831
You never talk about that.

218
00:24:59,132 --> 00:25:02,133
I don't know why I never married.

219
00:25:02,302 --> 00:25:05,006
I have a serviceable list of reasons.

220
00:25:05,179 --> 00:25:10,766
Take out my reasons
and polish them every once in a while.

221
00:25:11,185 --> 00:25:14,389
I kept on growing out
in all these...

222
00:25:14,564 --> 00:25:18,727
...peculiar and idiosyncratic directions.

223
00:25:19,402 --> 00:25:23,400
I'd put on a little bristle here
and a bristle there...

224
00:25:23,573 --> 00:25:25,696
...and sort of...

225
00:25:25,867 --> 00:25:28,073
...turned myself into a porcupine.

226
00:25:30,746 --> 00:25:36,666
- What?
- Well, it's just such an old joke.

227
00:25:36,919 --> 00:25:39,208
How do two porcupines...

228
00:25:39,380 --> 00:25:41,752
...make love?

229
00:25:44,427 --> 00:25:46,633
Very carefully.

230
00:25:53,936 --> 00:25:57,720
To the left, right around this corner.
You'll find it.

231
00:26:07,908 --> 00:26:11,194
It's kind of you to make time
in your busy schedule for me.

232
00:26:11,537 --> 00:26:13,328
No trouble at all.

233
00:26:13,872 --> 00:26:17,158
So have you thought at all
about what I said?

234
00:26:17,334 --> 00:26:20,288
Uh-huh. You know something?

235
00:26:20,462 --> 00:26:23,997
That very same idea occurred to me
right after the funeral.

236
00:26:24,174 --> 00:26:26,131
I even hired a detective.

237
00:26:26,301 --> 00:26:30,595
Sent him over to Charleston,
where she said her people were at.

238
00:26:30,764 --> 00:26:34,465
There was nothing at all.
No family, not even a trace.

239
00:26:35,435 --> 00:26:38,639
Why didn't you come forward, Etta?

240
00:26:38,939 --> 00:26:42,106
Ben was gone.
