it would cost a fortune.

486
00:49:59,994 --> 00:50:02,319
Do you know what?

487
00:50:02,496 --> 00:50:05,497
My bankers say I'm insane.

488
00:50:08,127 --> 00:50:12,789
God, in the right spot,
it would be fantastic!

489
00:50:30,107 --> 00:50:33,392
You always been impatient, lady?
I mean, your whole life?

490
00:50:33,569 --> 00:50:37,697
Mr. Shin, in four weeks
I've given you $600.

491
00:50:37,865 --> 00:50:40,534
You, by way of contrast,
have given me zip.

492
00:50:41,118 --> 00:50:44,202
I'm surprised you can find
your office in the morning.

493
00:50:44,371 --> 00:50:48,832
You always sarcastic like that?
You were sarcastic little baby?

494
00:50:49,001 --> 00:50:51,918
You look for lady for four weeks, huh?

495
00:50:52,087 --> 00:50:54,874
One time I look for somebody
for 18 years.

496
00:50:56,091 --> 00:50:57,918
Quite a recommendation.

497
00:50:58,593 --> 00:51:00,716
Persistence.

498
00:51:00,887 --> 00:51:05,715
Besides, can't find such a pretty lady
for buck and a half a week.

499
00:51:05,892 --> 00:51:09,226
- Need incentive bonus.
- No, just show me what you've got.

500
00:51:09,604 --> 00:51:11,763
What do you mean, huh?
I got nothing.

501
00:51:11,940 --> 00:51:15,107
Mr. Shin, any man that would ask me
for a price increase...

502
00:51:15,277 --> 00:51:18,646
...without anything to deliver
would be kind of stupid.

503
00:51:18,822 --> 00:51:21,028
No point in insulting
your intelligence.

504
00:51:21,241 --> 00:51:24,242
I'd rather do business on a basis
of mutual respect.

505
00:51:24,744 --> 00:51:26,618
That's good.

506
00:51:26,788 --> 00:51:29,279
- I like respect.
- Fine.

507
00:51:29,666 --> 00:51:31,125
Where is she?

508
00:51:31,459 --> 00:51:34,129
All right, ladies,
before we re-enter the pool...

509
00:51:34,295 --> 00:51:39,716
...let's review the most important rule:
Never race your bubbles to the surface.

510
00:51:39,884 --> 00:51:46,172
It can cause lung expansion, which
can result in air in the bloodstream.

511
00:51:46,349 --> 00:51:50,477
This can produce an embolism,
which can result in...

512
00:51:50,645 --> 00:51:54,228
- You all right? Maybe you should sit out.
- A very agonizing death.

513
00:51:56,234 --> 00:51:59,021
Now then, ladies, let's get in the pool.

514
00:52:05,618 --> 00:52:07,825
Good. Okay, ladies,
come around here.

515
00:52:08,037 --> 00:52:10,991
Come on. Come on, all of you.

516
00:52:11,165 --> 00:52:16,207
We're going to pair up and practice
breathing two on the same regulator.

517
00:52:16,379 --> 00:52:19,131
This would be necessary
when one runs out of air.

518
00:52:19,298 --> 00:52:21,587
Now pair up. You and you.
You and you.

519
00:52:22,009 --> 00:52:27,466
That's right. Take the regulator and give
it to your partner for emergency air.

520
00:52:27,640 --> 00:52:30,807
Partners? Don't worry.
I'm not really contagious.

521
00:52:30,977 --> 00:52:34,926
My friend promised me she'd
be my partner, so...

522
00:52:35,147 --> 00:52:39,097
Well, that leaves me odd man out,
doesn't it?

523
00:52:41,320 --> 00:52:43,194
- Rennie Walker.
- Jessica Bates.

524
00:52:43,364 --> 00:52:46,234
- Jessica Bates, I owe you a beer.
- Take you up on it.

525
00:52:46,409 --> 00:52:49,409
Now you take the regulator
in your right hand...

526
00:52:49,620 --> 00:52:53,534
...you take two breaths from it,
and then you give it to your partner.

527
00:52:53,708 --> 00:52:57,491
She takes two breaths from it,
and then you take it back...

528
00:52:57,670 --> 00:53:01,039
...and you breathe into it twice.

529
00:53:01,632 --> 00:53:05,416
On five, you blow out.
Don't hold her nose so tight.

530
00:53:05,594 --> 00:53:08,761
You have to close her nose,
but don't rip it off her face.

531
00:53:08,931 --> 00:53:11,256
And keep your hand on the back
of her neck.

532
00:53:11,433 --> 00:53:14,885
If her airway closes,
she will not be able to breathe.

533
00:53:15,062 --> 00:53:17,387
You're not taking this personally,
are you?

534
00:53:17,564 --> 00:53:18,975
Don't worry.
- Okay.

535
00:53:19,149 --> 00:53:21,189
Okay, that's it for this afternoon.

536
00:53:21,402 --> 00:53:25,945
Thank you for your participation.
You can all go. Thank you.

537
00:53:31,370 --> 00:53:33,493
What's your name again?

538
00:53:33,664 --> 00:53:35,039
- Rennie.
- Rennie.

539
00:53:37,376 --> 00:53:41,041
- What are you doing here?
- Oh, just hanging out.

540
00:53:41,672 --> 00:53:43,629
Spending my money.

541
00:53:50,847 --> 00:53:52,757
What are you looking at?

542
00:53:52,933 --> 00:53:57,144
Oh, I'm sorry. No, it's just that
we spent most of the day in the pool...

543
00:53:57,312 --> 00:54:00,479
...and you come out looking like that
and I look like this.

544
00:54:00,649 --> 00:54:03,104
I just wondered why that is.

545
00:54:07,114 --> 00:54:09,439
You don't look bad.

546
00:54:09,616 --> 00:54:11,110
New suit might help, though.

547
00:54:11,326 --> 00:54:16,700
Oh, it's just the suit? Great.
I'm on a budget.

548
00:54:21,920 --> 00:54:23,628
What?

549
00:54:23,797 --> 00:54:27,794
What do you say we go up to my room,
have a couple of decent drinks?

550
00:54:27,968 --> 00:54:29,213
All right.

551
00:54:34,015 --> 00:54:37,633
- You married or what?
- Nope.

552
00:54:39,771 --> 00:54:41,728
Not at the moment.

553
00:54:42,774 --> 00:54:45,479
Thank you. Who's this?

554
00:54:45,652 --> 00:54:47,360
You like that, do you?

555
00:54:47,529 --> 00:54:50,732
Men that look like this,
you usually end up supporting.

556
00:54:50,907 --> 00:54:56,779
His name's Paul Nuytten, and he owns
half a dozen hotels around the world.

557
00:54:56,955 --> 00:55:02,578
Does he have a brother? Cousin?
Young grandfather?

558
00:55:03,419 --> 00:55:06,171
He's having a party tonight.
Do you want to come?

559
00:55:06,339 --> 00:55:07,833
What?

560
00:55:08,007 --> 00:55:11,293
He's having a party tonight.
Do you want to come?

561
00:55:11,469 --> 00:55:15,336
Oh, I can't. I left all my designer
stuff back in Chicago.

562
00:55:15,515 --> 00:55:19,049
Well, that's all right.
You can borrow something of mine.

563
00:55:25,566 --> 00:55:27,808
Could I borrow your hair?

564
00:55:29,195 --> 00:55:30,855
How about your hairdresser?

565
00:55:31,531 --> 00:55:32,693
Sure.

566
00:55:42,291 --> 00:55:43,620
- You look pretty.
Thanks.

567
00:55:43,793 --> 00:55:45,453
- You gonna be okay?
- I think so.

568
00:55:45,628 --> 00:55:47,620
I'll catch you later.

569
00:55:50,633 --> 00:55:52,625
Gin and tonic.

570
00:56:00,684 --> 00:56:02,428
Thank you.

571
00:56:41,141 --> 00:56:45,602
Oh, I know this dress,
but who is the woman?

572
00:56:46,021 --> 00:56:49,604
Paul Nuytten, my new pal,
Jessica Bates.

573
00:56:49,775 --> 00:56:51,483
- Pleasure to meet you.
- Welcome.

574
00:56:51,652 --> 00:56:53,775
Thank you.
You have a beautiful home.

575
00:56:53,946 --> 00:56:55,819
Thank you.

576
00:56:57,491 --> 00:57:00,657
Would you like to dance?

577
00:57:01,244 --> 00:57:05,574
No. Thanks.
I have new shoes.

578
00:57:26,895 --> 00:57:28,971
Mademoiselle.

579
00:57:29,189 --> 00:57:31,312
Thank you. What's your name?

580
00:57:31,524 --> 00:57:35,059
- Tran.
- Tran?

581
00:57:37,947 --> 00:57:39,607
Rennie.

582
00:57:43,161 --> 00:57:45,450
Tonight you stay?

583
00:57:47,332 --> 00:57:50,286
You have a very busy day tomorrow.

584
00:57:50,460 --> 00:57:52,749
You have to polish your boat...

585
00:57:53,588 --> 00:57:55,877
...hunt some wild boar.

586
00:57:59,427 --> 00:58:01,301
Oh, Paul.

587
00:58:02,764 --> 00:58:06,097
You have your little phone book,
lots of numbers.

588
00:58:09,854 --> 00:58:12,772
Why do we keep having
this conversation?

589
00:58:13,399 --> 00:58:15,522
It's you.

590
00:58:15,693 --> 00:58:18,184
It's you I want.

591
00:58:24,327 --> 00:58:27,992
All you want is the woman
you haven't slept with.

592
00:58:28,498 --> 00:58:31,534
That's not the same as wanting me.

593
00:58:42,261 --> 00:58:43,969
Paul.

594
00:58:45,514 --> 00:58:47,388
I need a kiss.

595
00:59:22,635 --> 00:59:24,508
Fresh fish!

596
00:59:28,057 --> 00:59:31,888
Aku! Fresh aku! Aku!
Freshest fish!

597
00:59:35,939 --> 00:59:38,098
- Fish! Fish!
That one.

598
00:59:38,275 --> 00:59:40,149
- Two pounds.
Hey!

599
00:59:42,154 --> 00:59:44,727
I see you've caught your fish after all.

600
00:59:45,782 --> 00:59:48,867
Oh, can't place my face, huh?
Forgetting is useful skill.

601
00:59:49,036 --> 00:59:52,535
- I could learn some of that some time.
- Take out your cigarettes.

602
00:59:52,706 --> 00:59:55,375
Take out your cigarettes
and offer me one.

603
00:59:56,335 --> 01:00:00,379
No, thanks. This is federal government.
You don't wanna lose your license.

604
01:00:00,589 --> 01:00:02,795
Point. At the fish.

605
01:00:02,966 --> 01:00:05,089
- Say thank you and goodbye.
- Thank you.

606
01:00:05,302 --> 01:00:06,630
Goodbye.

607
01:00:14,436 --> 01:00:15,930
Who was that guy?

608
01:00:16,104 --> 01:00:19,354
He's a local, and he's asking me
if the fish is fresh.

609
01:00:25,614 --> 01:00:27,322
<i>- Hello?
Sara?</i>

610
01:00:27,490 --> 01:00:30,859
- Yes?
- Sara, it's Catharine.

611
01:00:31,036 --> 01:00:34,820
- Petersen.
- Catharine!

612
01:00:34,998 --> 01:00:38,367
It's been such a long time.
Are you all right?

613
01:00:38,585 --> 01:00:42,499
Well, I have a situation actually.

614
01:00:43,339 --> 01:00:47,171
Apparently, there's been a woman
reporter asking questions about me...

615
01:00:47,343 --> 01:00:49,003
...and Sam.

616
01:00:49,179 --> 01:00:51,717
Has anyone like that been
around to see you?

617
01:00:51,890 --> 01:00:56,801
<i>Well, yes. There was a young woman
by here about six months ago.</i>

618
01:00:57,020 --> 01:00:59,475
But she was from
the federal government.

619
01:01:01,566 --> 01:01:06,109
Listen, Sara, I really must go
right now...

620
01:01:06,279 --> 01:01:08,437
...but I'll phone you later to catch up.

621
01:01:08,615 --> 01:01:11,699
It's been a long time,
and I would like to keep in touch.

622
01:01:11,868 --> 01:01:13,362
I'll talk to you later, bye.

623
01:04:40,408 --> 01:04:43,444
I'll do it. I'll do it!

624
01:04:44,996 --> 01:04:49,040
The goddamn gauge said half full.
How come there was no air in it?

625
01:04:51,210 --> 01:04:53,618
I was supposed to check these things.

626
01:04:59,218 --> 01:05:02,753
If I was a little further out
or had my back turned...

627
01:05:03,430 --> 01:05:06,431
You scared the shit out of me.

628
01:05:08,269 --> 01:05:10,890
Thanks for not having your back turned.

629
01:05:41,009 --> 01:05:43,679
I'll be right down.

630
01:06:02,155 --> 01:06:03,947
Hey!

631
01:06:05,534 --> 01:06:08,107
You really like those things?

632
01:06:09,037 --> 01:06:11,611
My second husband was addicted.

633
01:06:11,832 --> 01:06:14,453
Second husband?
How many have you had?

634
01:06:14,626 --> 01:06:19,003
Lots. That's how I got rich.

635
01:06:19,589 --> 01:06:22,259
Once wasn't enough to get rich?

636
01:06:22,717 --> 01:06:24,840
Rich is hard.

637
01:06:25,887 --> 01:06:29,221
You never really figure
you're quite there.

638
01:06:29,808 --> 01:06:31,551
That sounds pretty romantic.

639
01:06:34,354 --> 01:06:35,932
Well...

640
01:06:37,065 --> 01:06:39,022
...I used to think of it as my job.

641
01:06:40,652 --> 01:06:43,107
Making myself appealing.

642
01:06:44,531 --> 01:06:46,903
I was a professional.

643
01:07:07,136 --> 01:07:11,798
L... I loved every one of them.

644
01:07:15,019 --> 01:07:17,012
Deeply.

645
01:07:19,315 --> 01:07:20,893
Honestly.

646
01:07:26,197 --> 01:07:28,355
It wouldn't have worked any other way.

647
01:07:36,332 --> 01:07:38,206
You like him.

648
01:07:41,921 --> 01:07:44,210
Paul. You like him.

649
01:07:48,511 --> 01:07:50,550
Go for it.

650
01:07:51,639 --> 01:07:53,678
He wants you to.

651
01:07:58,771 --> 01:08:01,096
He needs somebody now...

652
01:08:01,273 --> 01:08:03,349
...who knows how to commit.

653
01:08:08,113 --> 01:08:11,897
They're arguing over some woman
named Pelé, like the soccer player.

654
01:08:12,076 --> 01:08:15,242
One argues that she's going
on the warpath on Tuesday.

655
01:08:15,412 --> 01:08:17,654
The other guy says,
"No, next Wednesday."

656
01:08:17,831 --> 01:08:19,907
Six guys got into the same argument...

657
01:08:20,084 --> 01:08:23,951
...like they all know the same woman.
- No, no. Pelé is a goddess.

658
01:08:24,129 --> 01:08:28,875
Goddess of devastation.
She lives in a volcano. Kilauea.

659
01:08:29,051 --> 01:08:31,968
And every so often she makes fire.

660
01:08:32,137 --> 01:08:33,596
- More coffee?
- No, thanks.

661
01:08:33,764 --> 01:08:35,922
- Coffee?
No.

662
01:08:36,100 --> 01:08:39,219
Thank you.
You okay?

663
01:08:39,645 --> 01:08:43,345
I don't feel too well actually.
I think I'll go back to the hotel.

664
01:08:47,194 --> 01:08:49,732
- I'll talk to you later.
- Okay.

665
01:08:55,577 --> 01:08:59,527
- I'll drive you home.
- Don't be ridiculous.

666
01:08:59,706 --> 01:09:01,995
It's only a headache.

667
01:09:03,627 --> 01:09:07,126
I'll call you tonight.
We'll do something tomorrow.

668
01:09:07,297 --> 01:09:12,754
Look, you and Jessie
go on with your afternoon. Okay?

669
01:09:13,845 --> 01:09:15,304
And have a nice time.

670
01:09:43,458 --> 01:09:47,123
Tran, did he work
for your family in Indochina?

671
01:09:47,378 --> 01:09:48,623
Huh?

672
01:09:49,255 --> 01:09:54,629
It's just that you and he seem so close.
Did he work for another family?

673
01:09:55,470 --> 01:09:57,379
Your wife's?

674
01:10:00,308 --> 01:10:02,384
It's just that I sense...

675
01:10:03,061 --> 01:10:05,302
She was killed.

676
01:10:05,480 --> 01:10:07,887
She was only 19.

677
01:10:08,066 --> 01:10:09,560
I'm sorry.

678
01:10:11,861 --> 01:10:14,613
And I'm sorry I made you think of it.

679
01:10:15,615 --> 01:10:20,241
It's a rare gift to see things
that others cannot.

680
01:10:20,953 --> 01:10:23,871
It drives some people away.

681
01:10:25,291 --> 01:10:30,286
I don't think people like you to know
things before they're ready to tell you.

682
01:10:30,463 --> 01:10:33,998
So I should just learn
to keep my mouth shut.

683
01:10:39,639 --> 01:10:42,723
Won't you see some of the island?

684
01:10:45,686 --> 01:10:47,478
Yes, I'd like that.

685
01:11:12,046 --> 01:11:15,296
Why are you smiling?
- Because you have a look on your face.

686
01:11:15,466 --> 01:11:17,624
Look?
- Like you want to ask something...

687
01:11:17,801 --> 01:11:20,339
...then you don't.
You ought to just ask it.

688
01:11:20,512 --> 01:11:24,462
No, I was just thinking,
why hasn't this woman married?

689
01:11:24,642 --> 01:11:27,595
Attractive, intelligent.

690
01:11:27,978 --> 01:11:30,018
Very, very strong.

691
01:11:30,189 --> 01:11:33,059
- She is.
- She?

692
01:11:33,233 --> 01:11:35,060
But I'm talking about you.

693
01:11:37,237 --> 01:11:38,613
So...

694
01:11:38,781 --> 01:11:41,984
...what about you and men?

695
01:11:43,827 --> 01:11:45,238
Bad timing.

696
01:11:45,662 --> 01:11:48,497
Maybe a little bit of fear?

697
01:11:50,459 --> 01:11:52,416
Tell you something about that.

698
01:11:52,628 --> 01:11:54,751
It's very, very provocative.

699
01:13:03,406 --> 01:13:04,948
Such a strange place.

700
01:13:05,116 --> 01:13:08,615
The sap from the trees cools the lava.

701
01:13:11,706 --> 01:13:13,449
- Paul?
- Huh.

702
01:13:13,666 --> 01:13:16,916
- About Rennie.
- I'm not with Rennie.

703
01:13:17,837 --> 01:13:19,794
I'm with you.

704
01:13:22,133 --> 01:13:23,711
I can't compete with her.

705
01:13:23,885 --> 01:13:26,210
There is no necessity.

706
01:13:29,348 --> 01:13:35,517
I have to know whatever this is
is something honest and just for me.

707
01:13:36,272 --> 01:13:37,980
Look at me.

708
01:13:39,233 --> 01:13:41,107
Look at me.

709
01:13:43,154 --> 01:13:45,193
Decide.

710
01:14:09,722 --> 01:14:11,002
Here?

711
01:14:11,390 --> 01:14:15,174
I mean, can we turn
out the lights or something?

712
01:14:47,467 --> 01:14:50,552
No knock? Come into
a person's office, no knock?

713
01:14:50,721 --> 01:14:52,049
I'm sorry.

714
01:14:52,222 --> 01:14:56,968
I knock. I come to your office, I knock.
Where were you born, anyway?

715
01:14:57,144 --> 01:15:00,477
- Wisconsin. Should I come back later?
- No.

716
01:15:00,647 --> 01:15:04,230
Too late to come back later.
You already no knock.

717
01:15:04,401 --> 01:15:06,310
What you want, Wisconsin?

718
01:15:06,570 --> 01:15:10,188
Mr. Shin, my name is Rennie Walker.

719
01:15:13,076 --> 01:15:16,113
This woman befriended me.

720
01:15:16,329 --> 01:15:19,414
And now I think she's seeing my fiancé.

721
01:15:23,211 --> 01:15:24,789
I really must know.

722
01:15:25,088 --> 01:15:28,872
No, no, no. I no do this kind of work.
Not respectable.

723
01:15:29,092 --> 01:15:33,006
Mr. Shin, I'll tell you
two things about me.

724
01:15:33,179 --> 01:15:35,670
I'm very rich.

725
01:15:37,517 --> 01:15:39,842
And I'm very wealthy.

726
01:17:11,944 --> 01:17:15,894
I'm sorry about Jessie.
I thought it was what you wanted.

727
01:17:19,201 --> 01:17:22,072
Do you understand, Rennie?

728
01:17:27,710 --> 01:17:29,916
Long drive back.

729
01:17:30,963 --> 01:17:33,039
Fix me a drink?

730
01:17:56,822 --> 01:17:59,906
Rennie? Rennie?

731
01:18:01,493 --> 01:18:05,076
Come in. I want you to.

732
01:18:05,247 --> 01:18:08,616
Why tonight, after all this time?

733
01:18:08,834 --> 01:18:09,948
Huh?

734
01:18:11,461 --> 01:18:14,498
I think we've waited long enough.

735
01:19:27,870 --> 01:19:28,902
Just a minute.

736
01:19:33,292 --> 01:19:36,910
- Morning.
- Good morning.

737
01:19:44,929 --> 01:19:48,629
You left this in the Jeep
the other day.

738
01:19:48,808 --> 01:19:52,508
So you drove all the way
over just to deliver a sweater?

739
01:19:52,687 --> 01:19:54,596
No. Not exactly.

740
01:19:55,648 --> 01:19:59,942
- Would you like some coffee?
- No, thank you.

741
01:20:03,656 --> 01:20:05,483
I have something to tell you.

742
01:20:06,867 --> 01:20:08,860
Is something wrong?

743
01:20:09,620 --> 01:20:12,574
Last night, Rennie and I,
we decided to marry.

744
01:20:20,589 --> 01:20:24,005
I want you to be okay with this.

745
01:20:25,886 --> 01:20:28,175
I'll be okay.

746
01:21:01,129 --> 01:21:03,620
I'll be out there in a minute.

747
01:21:10,055 --> 01:21:11,514
Woman in love.

748
01:21:13,350 --> 01:21:18,012
- Do you really doubt it?
- No. I helped you get here, didn't I?

749
01:21:18,438 --> 01:21:21,439
When you put us together,
it made him want you more.

750
01:21:21,608 --> 01:21:24,941
So I guess you could say my
wedding gift was the groom.

751
01:21:26,530 --> 01:21:29,863
I meant it as an exchange of gifts.

752
01:21:30,909 --> 01:21:34,242
Something you could take
with you from your time with Paul.

753
01:21:34,412 --> 01:21:38,280
Well, in that case, I still owe you one.

754
01:21:41,336 --> 01:21:44,456
- That was a beautiful ceremony.
- Thank you.

755
01:21:44,631 --> 01:21:47,122
It was a lovely ceremony.

756
01:21:48,051 --> 01:21:49,675
Open it.

757
01:21:51,346 --> 01:21:54,347
Whatever this is, it means a lot to me.

758
01:22:10,657 --> 01:22:12,945
Black widow.

759
01:22:14,494 --> 01:22:16,782
She mates and she kills.

760
01:22:19,707 --> 01:22:22,494
Your question is, does she love?

761
01:22:23,753 --> 01:22:26,956
It's impossible to answer that...

762
01:22:28,007 --> 01:22:30,083
...unless you live in her world.

763
01:22:36,349 --> 01:22:39,219
Such an intriguing gift.

764
01:22:44,857 --> 01:22:47,858
Makes me wish I had
more to share with you.

765
01:22:50,071 --> 01:22:54,697
- Truth is, I'm sorry it's over.
- The truth is, it's not over yet.

766
01:22:59,080 --> 01:23:00,490
Till then.

767
01:23:02,625 --> 01:23:07,037
With your permission, may I have
the pleasure to kiss the lovely bride?

768
01:23:32,112 --> 01:23:33,939
Come in.

769
01:23:38,160 --> 01:23:41,778
Hey, Wisconsin, you knock.
I no recognize you.

770
01:23:42,247 --> 01:23:45,912
- Do you have my pictures?
- Sure.

771
01:23:46,460 --> 01:23:51,418
Hey, I see you got married
a little while ago. Congratulations.

772
01:23:53,425 --> 01:23:55,998
Good stuff, huh?

773
01:24:05,395 --> 01:24:09,227
What else do you have
in your desk, Mr. Shin?

774
01:24:09,399 --> 01:24:14,394
What do you mean by that? I got a lot
of stuff. I got paper clips. I got menthol.

775
01:24:14,571 --> 01:24:19,316
Condoms even, not it any your
business. Why you ask?

776
01:24:19,785 --> 01:24:23,699
Because you have a choice, Mr. Shin.
You can die or you can die happy.

777
01:24:23,914 --> 01:24:27,329
- Why are you doing this?
- It's in the second drawer. Look!

778
01:24:27,500 --> 01:24:29,078
You have five seconds.

779
01:24:33,798 --> 01:24:35,625
- One...
- Please.

780
01:24:36,092 --> 01:24:38,168
...two...
- Wait! Wait!

781
01:24:39,721 --> 01:24:41,548
- Hold on.
...three...

782
01:24:48,354 --> 01:24:49,683
<i>... four.</i>

783
01:24:50,982 --> 01:24:53,651
Hyland, let me see that needle.

784
01:24:55,904 --> 01:24:58,276
Get it to the lab.

785
01:24:58,490 --> 01:25:01,325
- Make sure they don't move anything.
- Okay.

786
01:25:06,289 --> 01:25:08,495
I want the whole room dusted.

787
01:25:08,666 --> 01:25:11,537
<i>Anything here for the Herald?
Or just a nothing OD?</i>

788
01:25:11,711 --> 01:25:14,416
If it gets exciting,
I'll find your number.

789
01:25:18,009 --> 01:25:19,966
Now who would you be?

790
01:25:45,620 --> 01:25:49,700
I'm glad you came over, Paul.
I need to talk to you.

791
01:25:49,874 --> 01:25:52,579
Don't you think Rennie
left a bit abruptly?

792
01:25:52,752 --> 01:25:57,746
No. Just her usual trip. She sees
her accountant on the mainland.

793
01:25:57,923 --> 01:25:59,667
Investments.

794
01:26:02,678 --> 01:26:05,714
Paul, how well do you
think you know me?

795
01:26:06,098 --> 01:26:07,129
Know you?

796
01:26:10,519 --> 01:26:13,520
- A little bit, I guess.
- Would I ever lie to you?

797
01:26:13,731 --> 01:26:16,566
- I don't know.
- Well, I did.

798
01:26:17,192 --> 01:26:19,315
My name is not Jessica Bates.

799
01:26:19,486 --> 01:26:22,357
It's Alex Barnes.
I work for the Justice Department.

800
01:26:25,326 --> 01:26:27,995
Your wife's name
is not Rennie either.

801
01:26:28,162 --> 01:26:31,495
Only, no one seems to know
what her real name is.

802
01:26:31,665 --> 01:26:33,741
- Listen to me.
- This makes no sense.

803
01:26:33,917 --> 01:26:38,663
Under three different names, she married
three different men. All wealthy men.

804
01:26:38,881 --> 01:26:42,047
- What are you trying to do?
- Paul, she killed all of them.

805
01:26:42,217 --> 01:26:47,342
She poisoned them. She's left town and
that's when they die, when she's gone.

806
01:26:51,602 --> 01:26:55,434
But she doesn't need my money.
I've seen her portfolio. Bank accounts...

807
01:26:55,606 --> 01:26:58,606
I just told you how she got them.

808
01:27:00,611 --> 01:27:03,979
- I know it sounds like I used you.
- Sounds like?

809
01:27:05,115 --> 01:27:07,606
You can't say that you
didn't know how I felt.

810
01:27:07,784 --> 01:27:11,699
That was Jessie, not some cop.

811
01:27:12,873 --> 01:27:18,377
Look, lady, don't feel so bad.
Everybody uses everybody.

812
01:27:20,464 --> 01:27:22,955
Only she does it better, right?

813
01:27:23,133 --> 01:27:26,300
That's what it is, isn't it?
She does it better.

814
01:27:26,469 --> 01:27:30,135
- No, that isn't it.
- And I told myself you could handle it.

815
01:27:30,307 --> 01:27:33,722
- I did!
- Then maybe you can explain our wills.

816
01:27:33,893 --> 01:27:38,223
They leave everything...
Everything to the Cancer Foundation.

817
01:27:38,398 --> 01:27:42,098
Nothing to each other.
It was her idea.

818
01:27:42,277 --> 01:27:45,480
Sound like the woman
you're talking about?

819
01:27:46,364 --> 01:27:48,156
Answer me!

820
01:27:54,038 --> 01:27:57,075
Tell me there is no jealousy.

821
01:27:58,668 --> 01:28:01,159
No jealousy at all.

822
01:28:24,235 --> 01:28:27,734
They said he strangled
in his sleep or something.

823
01:28:31,284 --> 01:28:33,988
Do you know a woman named
Jessica Bates?

824
01:28:34,704 --> 01:28:36,661
I do.

825
01:28:36,831 --> 01:28:41,125
It seems Miss Bates
is a federal agent named Barnes.

826
01:28:41,502 --> 01:28:46,247
And Miss Barnes believes
that you murdered Mr. Nuytten.

827
01:28:47,550 --> 01:28:50,219
Paul died last night.

828
01:28:50,386 --> 01:28:54,086
I was in San Francisco.
You can call the hotel.

829
01:28:54,306 --> 01:28:56,216
She thinks you poisoned him.

830
01:28:56,392 --> 01:28:59,808
Something that would take delayed
effect while he slept.

831
01:29:05,025 --> 01:29:07,433
- Did you check our home for the poison?
- No.

832
01:29:07,653 --> 01:29:10,773
There's no probable cause for a warrant.

833
01:29:10,948 --> 01:29:15,111
- I thought you might voluntarily...
- Of course. Yes.

834
01:29:15,286 --> 01:29:17,444
Check everything you want.

835
01:29:20,082 --> 01:29:22,620
And while you're at it...

836
01:29:23,085 --> 01:29:27,581
...Jessica Bates,
or whatever her name is...

837
01:29:28,424 --> 01:29:33,251
...was my husband's lover.
Before and after the wedding.

838
01:29:34,346 --> 01:29:37,715
So while you're searching my home...

839
01:29:40,018 --> 01:29:41,394
Interesting.

840
01:29:41,562 --> 01:29:45,974
We learned that he went to her
apartment yesterday afternoon.

841
01:30:23,478 --> 01:30:25,637
Please, have a seat.

842
01:30:27,524 --> 01:30:29,896
You've been more than kind...

843
01:30:30,318 --> 01:30:32,988
...after what you've been through.

844
01:30:35,115 --> 01:30:38,649
Listen, we did find a toxic compound
in Miss Barnes' apartment.

845
01:30:40,036 --> 01:30:42,871
Delayed-action poison.

846
01:30:43,039 --> 01:30:45,447
Also, we have certain photographs.

847
01:30:50,380 --> 01:30:53,250
Photos of Miss Barnes
and your husband.

848
01:30:53,425 --> 01:30:57,885
Those pictures are all my fault. I...

849
01:30:59,681 --> 01:31:03,180
I hired this horrid little man.

850
01:31:04,269 --> 01:31:05,811
How did you get them?

851
01:31:06,354 --> 01:31:08,927
The man you hired
is dead, Mrs. Nuytten.

852
01:31:09,107 --> 01:31:12,606
We assumed of an accidental
overdose of heroin.

853
01:31:13,528 --> 01:31:17,857
Now I'm afraid Miss Barnes has more
than just your husband to answer for.

854
01:31:21,994 --> 01:31:23,738
How well did you know him?

855
01:31:26,666 --> 01:31:28,955
Back as far as you can.

856
01:31:30,962 --> 01:31:34,128
Did you know Paul Nuytten?
Were you having a love affair?

857
01:31:35,007 --> 01:31:40,002
Mrs. Nuytten, the Cancer Foundation
flew Mr. Foster to the islands...

858
01:31:40,179 --> 01:31:43,844
...because we seem to have...
Well, something of a situation.

859
01:31:44,016 --> 01:31:48,394
- A situation?
- Yes, it's concerning Mr. Nuytten's will.

860
01:31:48,562 --> 01:31:52,856
It seems that Mr. Nuytten's legal
residence is the state of Florida.

861
01:31:53,025 --> 01:31:54,852
Were you aware of that?

862
01:31:55,027 --> 01:31:56,569
No. Should I be?

863
01:31:57,029 --> 01:32:01,738
Florida has a so-called mortmain
statute, Mrs. Nuytten.

864
01:32:02,118 --> 01:32:07,242
Any bequest to charity in a will
executed within six months of death...

865
01:32:07,414 --> 01:32:09,621
...can be invalidated by the spouse.

866
01:32:12,837 --> 01:32:14,913
- How interesting.
Of course...

867
01:32:15,089 --> 01:32:18,540
...it's no requirement
that you invalidate the gift.

868
01:32:19,718 --> 01:32:24,427
Shortly before his death,
Mr. Foster, my husband...

869
01:32:24,598 --> 01:32:28,133
...expressed reservations
about your organization.

870
01:32:30,437 --> 01:32:33,723
Profound reservations.

871
01:32:43,492 --> 01:32:47,821
Miss Barnes called from the jail.

872
01:32:49,665 --> 01:32:54,825
I tell her you plan to take long trip.

873
01:33:55,105 --> 01:33:57,430
Treating you...?

874
01:33:58,650 --> 01:34:00,025
You okay?

875
01:34:01,945 --> 01:34:04,233
I can't complain.

876
01:34:05,990 --> 01:34:08,861
It's a lot of psychological tests.

877
01:34:09,661 --> 01:34:12,496
Which I find surprising
for a crime of passion.

878
01:34:15,625 --> 01:34:18,330
Not so surprising.

879
01:34:19,504 --> 01:34:23,916
Well, they don't seem to think
your only motive was jealousy.

880
01:34:25,843 --> 01:34:27,635
Not of Paul, anyway.

881
01:34:28,513 --> 01:34:32,261
They seem to think
your obsession was...

882
01:34:33,726 --> 01:34:35,220
...with me.

883
01:34:35,937 --> 01:34:39,270
They think you started out as
an ambitious federal agent...

884
01:34:41,317 --> 01:34:44,686
...and you became obsessed by this...

885
01:34:45,738 --> 01:34:47,731
...phantom.

886
01:34:48,407 --> 01:34:50,483
And then...

887
01:34:51,160 --> 01:34:53,153
...you chased her...

888
01:34:54,080 --> 01:34:55,657
...and you chased her...

889
01:34:57,249 --> 01:35:01,377
...and when you thought you'd
never be quick enough to catch her...

890
01:35:01,545 --> 01:35:03,372
I killed him...

891
01:35:03,756 --> 01:35:05,748
...to frame you.

892
01:35:33,118 --> 01:35:35,241
How did you manage it?

893
01:35:35,412 --> 01:35:38,366
What, did you leave town
and sneak back?

894
01:35:39,750 --> 01:35:43,201
Did you use the same bottle
you put in my place?

895
01:35:43,378 --> 01:35:47,672
You always did have a tendency
to over-think things.

896
01:35:48,383 --> 01:35:53,211
The most important thing about figuring
anything out is knowing when to stop.

897
01:36:00,103 --> 01:36:02,143
You know...

898
01:36:03,649 --> 01:36:07,516
...of all the relationships
I'll look back on...

899
01:36:07,694 --> 01:36:09,936
...in 50 years' time...

900
01:36:14,117 --> 01:36:17,866
...I'll always remember this one.

901
01:36:37,265 --> 01:36:38,973
Hello, Sara.

902
01:36:41,770 --> 01:36:43,312
It's good to see you.

903
01:37:11,883 --> 01:37:15,216
I put the poison in Paul's brandy.
You mustn't...

904
01:37:15,386 --> 01:37:17,712
We know. We found it before he did.

905
01:38:26,915 --> 01:38:28,659
Get your cameras, she's here!

906
01:38:28,834 --> 01:38:33,579
Congratulations, that was a brilliant trap.
Are you going back to Washington now?

907
01:38:33,756 --> 01:38:36,081
Were you tipped off
she was here in Hawaii?

908
01:38:36,258 --> 01:38:38,251
Please, give us an answer for the press.

909
01:38:38,427 --> 01:38:41,381
Are you going to testify at the trial?

910
01:38:44,933 --> 01:38:47,140
I will give you the statement.

